---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL for Compliance Officers - HIPAA, SOC2, GDPR"
  description="Compliance features, audit trails, and regulatory readiness for FraiseQL."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>🔐 FraiseQL for Compliance Officers</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>Enterprise compliance, audit trails, and regulatory readiness built-in</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Your Concern</h2>
      <p>
        As a compliance officer, you need to verify:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>100% audit trail of all data access and mutations</li>
        <li>No unauthorized data leakage or modification</li>
        <li>Compliance with HIPAA, SOC 2, GDPR, PCI-DSS</li>
        <li>Encryption at rest and in transit</li>
        <li>Rate limiting to prevent abuse</li>
        <li>Error messages don't leak sensitive information</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Compliance Features Built-In</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">1. 100% Audit Logging</h3>
      <p>
        Every mutation is logged with:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Timestamp:</strong> Precise UTC time</li>
        <li><strong>User ID:</strong> Who made the change</li>
        <li><strong>Mutation type:</strong> Exactly what changed</li>
        <li><strong>Input parameters:</strong> What data was provided (PII sanitized)</li>
        <li><strong>Result:</strong> Success or failure</li>
        <li><strong>HMAC signature:</strong> Cryptographic proof (can't be forged)</li>
      </ul>
      <pre><code>{`# Example audit log entry (immutable, signed)
{
  "timestamp": "2024-02-06T12:34:56Z",
  "user_id": "user-123",
  "mutation": "create_patient_record",
  "inputs": {
    "patient_name": "***REDACTED***",
    "ssn": "***REDACTED***",
    "date_of_birth": "1980-01-01"
  },
  "result": "success",
  "signature": "sha256=abc123def456...",
  "audit_log_id": "audit-789"
}`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">2. Field-Level Encryption</h3>
      <p>
        Sensitive fields are encrypted at the database layer:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# Define sensitive fields in schema
@fraiseql.type
class PatientRecord:
    id: int
    name: str                              # Public
    ssn: str @encrypted                    # Encrypted at rest
    medical_history: str @encrypted        # Encrypted at rest
    insurance_id: str @encrypted           # Encrypted at rest

# At rest in database: Ciphertext
# In memory: Decrypted only when accessed
# In transit: HTTPS TLS

# Encryption keys rotated: Every 90 days (configurable)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">3. Rate Limiting (Brute-Force Protection)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`[fraiseql.security.rate_limiting]
enabled = true

# Per-user limits
auth_start_max_requests = 100
auth_start_window_secs = 60

# Per-IP limits
ip_max_requests = 1000
ip_window_secs = 60

# Complex query limits (prevent DOS)
max_query_depth = 10
max_query_breadth = 100
max_result_size_mb = 100

# Violations: 429 Too Many Requests (no data leaked)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">4. Error Sanitization</h3>
      <p>
        Error messages never leak implementation details:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# Internal error (what developers see in logs)
[ERROR] Query failed: "User with ID 123 not found at users.id"

# External error (what clients see)
{
  "error": "Query failed",
  "error_id": "err_abc123"
}

# Prevents:
# - Schema discovery via errors
# - SQL injection detection
# - Timing attacks
# - Information leakage`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">5. Constant-Time Comparison</h3>
      <p>
        Authentication checks resist timing attacks:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# Vulnerable approach (timing reveals info)
if (user.password_hash == provided_hash) { ... }
# Attack: Time how long comparison takes
# Longer = more characters matched

# FraiseQL approach (constant-time)
constant_time_compare(user.password_hash, provided_hash)
# Always takes same time regardless of match
# Prevents: Timing-based password cracking`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">6. PKCE State Encryption</h3>
      <p>
        OAuth state parameters are encrypted (prevents interception):
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# PKCE flow with encrypted state
1. Client generates: state = encrypt(random_256_bits, key)
2. Send to OAuth provider: state = ciphertext
3. OAuth provider redirects: ?state=ciphertext
4. Client decrypts: state_verified = decrypt(state, key)
5. If state matches original: OAuth token trusted

# Prevents: State parameter inspection attacks`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Compliance Certification</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">HIPAA (Healthcare)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Compliance checklist:
✅ Encryption at rest (field-level encryption)
✅ Encryption in transit (TLS)
✅ Audit logging (100% mutation trail)
✅ Access controls (role-based RBAC)
✅ Data minimization (no unnecessary collection)
✅ Breach notification procedures (automated alerts)
✅ Business Associate Agreements (for vendors)

FraiseQL is HIPAA-ready:
- Mutation audit trail proves who accessed what when
- Field encryption protects PHI at rest
- Error sanitization prevents data leakage
- Rate limiting prevents brute-force attacks`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">SOC 2 Type II</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Compliance checklist:
✅ Security (mutations logged, encrypted, access controlled)
✅ Availability (high availability, monitoring)
✅ Processing Integrity (all changes audited)
✅ Confidentiality (field encryption, TLS)
✅ Privacy (PII handling, consent tracking)

FraiseQL facilitates SOC 2 compliance:
- Built-in audit logging
- Automated monitoring and alerting
- Immutable audit trail (signatures prevent tampering)
- Access control via RBAC decorators`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">GDPR (Data Protection)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Compliance checklist:
✅ Right to be forgotten (data deletion tracked in audit log)
✅ Data portability (export mutation history)
✅ Consent management (recorded in audit trail)
✅ Privacy by design (field-level encryption)
✅ Data processing agreements (with vendors)
✅ Breach notifications (automated alerts)

FraiseQL GDPR capabilities:
- Delete mutations are logged with reason
- Export audit trail for data subject requests
- Encryption ensures confidentiality
- Rate limiting prevents unauthorized access`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">PCI-DSS (Payment Card)</h3>
      <pre><code>{`Compliance checklist:
✅ Restrict access to cardholder data (RBAC)
✅ Protect stored cardholder data (encryption)
✅ Monitor and test security (audit logging)
✅ Maintain policy that addresses security (SOC 2)

FraiseQL PCI-DSS features:
- Never log PCI data (automatic redaction)
- Field encryption for payment tokens
- Audit trail for access attempts
- Rate limiting prevents brute force`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Audit Trail Deep Dive</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>The audit log is your single source of truth for compliance.</strong>
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Audit Log Structure</h3>
      <pre><code>{`{
  "audit_log_id": "audit_001",
  "timestamp": "2024-02-06T12:34:56.789Z",
  "user_id": "user_123",
  "user_email": "alice@example.com",
  "action": "mutation",
  "mutation_name": "create_patient_record",
  "status": "success",
  "inputs": {
    "name": "***REDACTED***",
    "age": 42,
    "diagnosis": "***REDACTED***"
  },
  "result": {
    "patient_id": "pat_001"
  },
  "duration_ms": 125,
  "ip_address": "192.0.2.1",
  "user_agent": "GraphQL-Client/1.0",
  "signature": "sha256=e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4649b934ca495991b7852b855",
  "metadata": {
    "request_id": "req_abc123",
    "correlation_id": "corr_xyz789",
    "source_system": "ehr-system"
  }
}`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Audit Log Immutability</h3>
      <p>
        Audit logs are cryptographically signed and immutable:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Signature:</strong> HMAC-SHA256 proves entry hasn't been modified
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Chain linking:</strong> Each entry signs the previous one (blockchain-style)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Append-only:</strong> Only additions allowed, never modifications
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Retention:</strong> Configurable (7 years for HIPAA by default)
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Audit Log Queries</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Get all mutations by user
SELECT * FROM audit_logs WHERE user_id = 'user_123'

# Get all access to sensitive field
SELECT * FROM audit_logs
WHERE mutation_inputs ->> 'ssn' IS NOT NULL

# Verify no mutations between dates (for SOC 2)
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM audit_logs
WHERE timestamp BETWEEN '2024-01-01' AND '2024-01-02'

# Detect brute-force attempts
SELECT ip_address, COUNT(*) FROM audit_logs
WHERE status = 'failure' AND timestamp > NOW() - INTERVAL 1 HOUR
GROUP BY ip_address HAVING COUNT(*) > 10`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Access Control (RBAC)</h2>

      <p>
        Define roles and permissions in schema:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`@fraiseql.type
class User:
    id: int
    name: str
    email: str
    @rbac(roles=["admin", "self"])
    password_hash: str

@fraiseql.mutation
@rbac(roles=["admin", "doctor"], org_id_match=true)
def create_patient_record(name: str, age: int) -> PatientRecord:
    # Only admin or doctor can create records
    # Must match organization ID for authorization
    pass

# At runtime:
# - User provides JWT with role: "doctor"
# - Middleware verifies role before executing mutation
# - If not authorized: 403 Forbidden (no data leakage)`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Data Deletion & GDPR Right to Be Forgotten</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Delete mutation (creates audit log entry)
mutation DeleteUserData($user_id: ID!) {
  deleteUserData(user_id: $user_id, reason: "user_requested") {
    success
    audit_log_id
  }
}

# Audit trail shows:
# - User ID deleted
# - Reason: user_requested (GDPR compliance)
# - Timestamp
# - Who deleted it
# - Cannot be undone (immutable record)

# Regulatory proof:
# - Audit log proves deletion happened
# - Timestamp proves timely response (30 days for GDPR)
# - Signature proves authenticity`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Breach Detection & Alerting</h2>

      <p>
        Automated detection of suspicious activity:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`[fraiseql.security.breach_detection]
enabled = true

# Detect brute-force attacks
failed_auth_threshold = 5          # 5 failures
failed_auth_window_secs = 300      # in 5 minutes

# Detect unusual access patterns
access_spike_threshold = 500       # 500% increase
access_spike_window_secs = 3600    # in 1 hour

# Detect privilege escalation
permission_upgrade_alert = true    # Alert on role changes

# Actions on detection
alert_email = "security@example.com"
alert_slack = "#security-alerts"
auto_rate_limit = true             # Immediately rate-limit suspicious IPs`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h2>Compliance Verification Checklist</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Before Production Deployment</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>☐ Audit logging enabled and tested</li>
        <li>☐ Field encryption configured for PII</li>
        <li>☐ Rate limiting configured</li>
        <li>☐ Error sanitization verified (no data leaks)</li>
        <li>☐ TLS certificates installed</li>
        <li>☐ RBAC roles defined</li>
        <li>☐ Secrets management (Vault) configured</li>
        <li>☐ Backup and recovery procedures tested</li>
        <li>☐ Breach detection alerts configured</li>
        <li>☐ Audit log retention configured</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Quarterly Verification</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>☐ Audit log integrity check (signatures valid)</li>
        <li>☐ Data retention policies still compliant</li>
        <li>☐ Encryption key rotation completed</li>
        <li>☐ No unusual access patterns detected</li>
        <li>☐ Backup restoration test successful</li>
        <li>☐ Compliance training up to date</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

